  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "e8Km38GMezyB0oyPsKaSPw/NSCY=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:45.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Claim\n\nFeed writes must be **serialized per topic** because SOC feed indices are monotonic and write-once \u2014 concurrent writes to the same topic race on the next index, and Bee rejects duplicates.\n\n## Evidence\n\n- Bee processes feed writes sequentially per topic (SOC index is monotonic)\n- Each index slot can only be written once; two parallel writers both targeting index N produces a conflict\n- The adapter's **per-topic `feedWriteLocks`** map guarantees that writes to the same topic are serialized\n- Cross-topic parallelism is still fine: the throttled flush allows up to 5 concurrent writes across different topics\n\n## Why it matters\n\nDropping the per-topic lock would not just slow things down \u2014 it would produce silent index collisions where only one of the concurrent updates survives. This lock is correctness-critical, not a performance optimization. The 3-second debounce already batches rapid edits on the same topic into a single write, minimizing contention on the lock.\n",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:45.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:45.000Z"
    }
  },
